canonical:
  title: 賀八關表
  author: 李崇仁
  language: lzh
  text: 丙鹿應千之景命雖舊惟新儀鳳關八之朝章匪今斯古寶座高拱輿情擧欣恭惟云云盛德在躬至仁育物廣矣大矣實元亨利貞之俱全禮云樂云非玉帛鐘鼓之徒備神人交暢福祿來崇伏念云云猥以庸資叨逢煕旦湖山地逈阻參肅穆之班象魏雲開願上康寧之祝
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 賀八關表
  author: 李崇仁
  language: lzh
  text: 丙鹿應千之景命。雖舊惟新。儀鳳關八之朝章。匪今斯古。寶座高拱。輿情擧欣。恭惟云云。盛德在躬。至仁育物。廣矣大矣。實元亨利貞之俱全。禮云樂云。非玉帛鐘鼓之徒備。神人交暢。福祿來崇。伏念云云。猥以庸資。叨逢煕旦。湖山地逈。阻參肅穆之班。象魏雲開。願上康寧之祝。
korean:
  title: 하 팔관 표
  author: 이숭인
  language: kor
  text: 병록(丙鹿)의 천년에 응하는 큰 명(命)은 오직 옛것이나 새롭고, 의봉(儀鳳)의 팔관회(八關會)는 지금이 아니라 옛 제도이니, 보좌(寶座)에 높이 앉아 계심에 여정(輿情)이 모두 기뻐하옵나이다. 공손히 생각하옵건대, 운운, 성덕(盛德)이 몸에 있고 지인(至仁)으로 만물을 기르시니, 넓고 크사 실로 원(元)ㆍ형(亨)ㆍ가(利)ㆍ정(貞)이 구비(俱備)되고, 예(禮)다 악(樂)이다 함은 옥백(玉帛)과 종고(鍾鼓)만을 갖춘 것을 말함이 아니므로 신인(神人)이 번갈아 유쾌하고 복록(福祿)이 와 높이 쌓이나이다. 엎드려 생각하옵건대, 운운, 외람되이 용렬한 자질로 빛나는 성시(聖時)를 만나, 호산(湖山)에 땅이 멀어 숙목(肅穆)한 반열(班列)에 참가치 못하오나, 위궐(魏闕)에 구름이 열린 데로 강녕(康寧)의 축원을 올리옵나이다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0350_010_0440&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: Memorial Presenting the Eight Pavilion Ceremony
  author: Lee Sung-in
  language: eng
  text: 'The grand mandate responding to the thousand years of Bing-lu renews what was ancient; the Eight Pavilion Ceremony of Yi-feng upholds the ways of old, not of this present day. Upon the precious throne sits majesty, and all hearts overflow with joy. With reverent contemplation: the sage embodies supreme virtue and nourishes all things with utmost benevolence—vast and grand, truly perfecting the four principles of creation, prosperity, gain, and firmness. When we speak of ritual propriety and music, we do not merely mean the arrangement of jade and silk, bells and drums; thus heaven and earth commune in delight, and blessings and fortune ascend in abundance. Yet this humble one, possessed of meager talent, has been graced to witness this luminous age. Though the distant hills prevent me from standing in that solemn assembly, I lift my gaze toward the celestial palace where clouds part, to offer this wish for perpetual peace and well-being.'
  footnotes:
    - The 'Eight Pavilion Ceremony' (八關會) was an important Buddhist-inspired state ceremony in medieval East Asia, symbolizing cosmic harmony and royal virtue.
    - The 'four principles' (元亨利貞) refer to the fundamental qualities of the hexagram Qian in the I Ching, representing the creative force and auspicious conditions.
    - The distant hills and separated geography suggest the author's physical distance from the capital, a common poetic conceit in memorials expressing both humility and longing.
